04946nam a22007575i 9781477312094DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212017txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016035709  a97814773120947 a10.7560/3120702doi  a(DE-B1597)587533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aGR111.A47bM67 2017 4aGR111.A47bM67 2017eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a398.2089/960732231 aMorgan, Stacy I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrankie and Johnny :bRace, Gender, and the Work of African American Folklore in 1930s America /cStacy I. Morgan. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Frankie and Johnny Take Center Stage: African American Folk Culture in 1930s America -- tChapter Two. Lead Belly’s Ninth Symphony: Huddie Ledbetter and the Changing Contours of American Folk Music -- tChapter Three. Pistol Packin’ Mama: Imperiled Masculinity in Thomas Hart Benton’s A Social History of the State of Missouri -- tChapter Four. Whiteface Marionettes: John Huston’s Comic Melodrama -- tChapter Five. The Finest Woman Ever to Walk the Streets: Mae West’s Outlaw Exploits in She Done Him Wrong -- tChapter Six. The Lynching of Johnny: Sterling Brown’s Social Realist Critique -- tEpilogue. African American Women’s Voices and the Tightrope of Respectability -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOriginating in a homicide in St. Louis in 1899, the ballad of “Frankie and Johnny” became one of America’s most familiar songs during the first half of the twentieth century. It crossed lines of race, class, and artistic genres, taking form in such varied expressions as a folk song performed by Huddie Ledbetter (Lead Belly); a ballet choreographed by Ruth Page and Bentley Stone under New Deal sponsorship; a mural in the Missouri State Capitol by Thomas Hart Benton; a play by John Huston; a motion picture, She Done Him Wrong, that made Mae West a national celebrity; and an anti-lynching poem by Sterling Brown. In this innovative book, Stacy I. Morgan explores why African American folklore—and “Frankie and Johnny” in particular—became prized source material for artists of diverse political and aesthetic sensibilities. He looks at a confluence of factors, including the Harlem Renaissance, the Great Depression, and resurgent nationalism, that led those creators to engage with this ubiquitous song. Morgan’s research uncovers the wide range of work that artists called upon African American folklore to perform in the 1930s, as it alternately reinforced and challenged norms of race, gender, and appropriate subjects for artistic expression. He demonstrates that the folklorists and creative artists of that generation forged a new national culture in which African American folk songs featured centrally not only in folk and popular culture but in the fine arts as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansvFolklore. 0aAfrican AmericansxFolklore. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAfrican Americans-Folklore. 0aAfrican Americans-Race identity. 0aFolk songs, EnglishzUnited States. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczUnited StatesxAfrican influences. 0aPopular musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 0aSex role-United States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31207040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477312094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477312094/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBA